10.Example 1

Modified

Mo 2023-10-09 11:20

Given:

A system for heating water from an inlet temperature of \(T_{m,i} = 20\ \mathrm{Â°C}\) to an outlet temperature of \(T_{m,o} = 60\ \mathrm{Â°C}\) involves passing the water through a thick walled tube having inner and outer diameters of \(20\ \mathrm{mm}\) and \(40\ \mathrm{mm}\). The outer surface of the tube is well insulated, and electrical heating within the wall provides for a uniform generation rate of \(\dot{q} = 1.0\ \frac{\mathrm{MW}}{\mathrm{m}^{3}}\).

Required:

  1. For a water mass flow rate of \(\dot{m} = 0.1\ \frac{\mathrm{kg}}{\mathrm{s}}\), how long must the tube be to achieve the desired outlet temperature?
  2. If the inner surface temperature of the tube is \(T_{s,o} = 70\ \mathrm{Â°C}\) at the outlet, what is the local convection heat transfer coefficient at the outlet?

Solution:

Start first by defining all of the given values.

\[T_{m,i} = 20\ \mathrm{Â°C} = 293.15\ \mathrm{K}\] \[T_{m,o} = 60\ \mathrm{Â°C} = 333.15\ \mathrm{K}\] \[D_i = 20\ \mathrm{mm}\] \[D_o = 40\ \mathrm{mm}\] \[\dot{q} = 1.0\ \frac{\mathrm{MW}}{\mathrm{m}^{3}}\] \[\dot{m} = 0.1\ \frac{\mathrm{kg}}{\mathrm{s}}\] \[T_{s,o} = 70\ \mathrm{Â°C} = 343.15\ \mathrm{K}\]

A diagram of the system is shown below.

The fluid properties will be evaluated at the average mean temperature. This is given by

\[ \bar{T}_m = \frac{T_{mo} + T_{mi}}{2} = 313.1\ \mathrm{K} = 40.0\ \mathrm{Â°C} \]

Going to Table A.6 at \(\bar{T}_m\) shows that interpolation is needed. This is shown below.

\[T_A = 310\ \mathrm{K} = 36.9\ \mathrm{Â°C}\] \[T_B = 315\ \mathrm{K} = 41.9\ \mathrm{Â°C}\] \[c_{p,A} = 4.178\ \frac{\mathrm{kJ}}{\left(\mathrm{K} \cdot \mathrm{kg}\right)}\] \[c_{p,B} = 4.179\ \frac{\mathrm{kJ}}{\left(\mathrm{K} \cdot \mathrm{kg}\right)}\] \[ c_p = \frac{\bar{T_m} - T_A}{T_B - T_A}(c_{pB} - c_{pA}) + c_{pA} = 4.179\ \frac{\mathrm{kJ}}{\left(\mathrm{K} \cdot \mathrm{kg}\right)} \]

Starting with an energy balance around the volume of the pipe shows

\[ \frac{dE_{sys}}{dt}=\Sigma \dot{E}_{in} - \Sigma \dot{E}_{out} \]

Assuming steady state conditions shows

\[ 0=\Sigma \dot{E}_{in} - \Sigma \dot{E}_{out} \]

The energy entering the pipe is through the heat generation term and is given by

\[ \Sigma \dot{E}_{in} = \dot{q} V = q \frac{\pi}{4}\left( D_o^2 - D_i^2 \right)L \]

The energy leaving the pipe is due to the convection heat rate to the fluid and as previous shown in the lecture notes is given by

\[ \Sigma \dot{E}_{out} = q_{conv} = \dot{m} c_p \left( T_{m,o} - T_{m,i} \right) \]

The energy balance then becomes

\[ 0=\dot{q} \frac{\pi}{4}\left( D_o^2 - D_i^2 \right)L - \dot{m} c_p \left( T_{m,o} - T_{m,i} \right) \]

Solving for the length \(L\) of the pipe shows

Answer, part (a): \(L = \frac{4 \dot{m} c_p (T_{mo} - T_{mi})}{\pi \dot{q} (D_o^2 - D_i^2)} = 17.73\ \mathrm{m}\)

Assuming that the heat generation term produces a constant surface heat flux condition on the pipe, the surface heat flux may be found

\[ q^{\prime \prime} = \frac{\dot{q} V}{A_s} = \frac{q\frac{\pi}{4}( D_o^2 - D_i^2 )L}{\pi D_i L} = \frac{\dot{q} ( D_o^2 - D_i^2 )}{4 D_i} = 15.0\ \frac{\mathrm{kW}}{\mathrm{m}^{2}} \]

Using Newtonâs law of cooling the convective coefficient at the outlet may be found. This is shown below.

\[ q^{''}_s=h_o \left( T_{s,o} - T_{m,o} \right) \]

Solving for the convective coefficient shows

Answer, part (b): \(h_o = \frac{q^{\prime \prime}_s}{T_{so}-T_{mo}} = 1.5\ \frac{\mathrm{kW}}{\left(\mathrm{K} \cdot \mathrm{m}^{2}\right)}\)
